On **.NET 10 SDK**, you get native MTP support via `global.json` — **no `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` needed**. That property is only for .NET 9 and earlier.

Add a `test` section to your `global.json`:

```json
{
  "sdk": {
    "version": "10.0.100"
  },
  "test": {
    "runner": "Microsoft.Testing.Platform"
  }
}
```

**Key differences from .NET 9 bridge mode:**

| .NET 9 (bridge) | .NET 10 (native) |
|---|---|
| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` in props | `"test": { "runner": "..." }` in `global.json` |
| `dotnet test -- --report-trx` (separator required) | `dotnet test --report-trx` (direct pass-through) |

So on .NET 10 you pass MTP arguments directly — no `--` separator needed.

You still need the framework-specific runner enablement (`EnableMSTestRunner`, `EnableNUnitRunner`, etc.) and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` in your projects or `Directory.Build.props`. The `global.json` setting only controls how `dotnet test` communicates with MTP — it doesn't replace the per-project runner opt-in.
